definition.value: The nail at the end of a finger.
A thin, horny translucent plate covering the end of each toe.
Subdivision of cardinal body part, each instance of which is a regional part of some face.
An organ that detects light.
Subdivision of face which has as its direct parts orbital cavity and its content and eyelids.
The organ of sight constituting a pair of globular organs made up of a three-layered roughly spherical structure specialized for receiving and responding to light.
The organ of sight or vision.

A muscular organ in the mouth that is covered with pink tissue called mucosa, tiny bumps called papillae, and thousands of taste buds. The tongue is anchored to the mouth and is vital for chewing, swallowing, and for speech.

The largest cartilage of the larynx consisting of two laminae fusing anteriorly at an acute angle in the midline of the neck. The point of fusion forms a subcutaneous projection known as the Adam's apple.

The largest of the laryngeal cartilages comprising two quadrilateral laminae that fuse to form a median elevation ("Adam's apple"). It lies inferior to the hyoid bone, its superior horn is attached to the tip of the greater horn of the hyoid bone, and its inferior horn articulates with the cricoid cartilage.
Nonparenchymatous organ which consists primarily of cartilage tissue.
The nine cartilages of the larynx, including the cricoid, thyroid and epiglottic, and two each of arytenoid, corniculate and cuneiform.
Organ region, each instance of which has one or more floating fiat boundaries.
A zone of thyroid cartilage formed by fusion of the two plate-like laminae of the cartilages.

One of a pair of cone-shaped elastic mucous membrane projecting from the laryngeal wall and forming a narrow slit between them. Each contains a thickened free edge (vocal ligament) extending from the thyroid cartilage to the arytenoid cartilage, and a vocal muscle that shortens or relaxes the vocal cord to control sound production.
Material anatomical entity which consists of a maximum number of some instances of discontinuous members of the same class.
Solid organ, each instance of which has as its direct parts instances of some parenchyma and connective tissue stroma.
Parenchymatous organ the stroma of which subdivides the parenchyma into lobes, segments, lobules and acini.
Solid organ which consists of organ parts that are arranged as fascicles or sheets.

Organ the direct parts of which consist of either fascicles or sheets or parenchyma and connective tissue stroma. Examples: Examples: muscle organ, ligament organ, membrane organ, skin, viscerocranial mucosa. Old definition: Organ the unshared parts of which do not surround macroscopic anatomical spaces; only its shared parts (subdivisions of hollow tree organs) contain anatomical spaces.
Organ, each instance of which has as its direct parts instances of some organ cavity and organ wall.
Cavitated organ in which its unshared parts surround one continuous anatomical space.
Segment of neuraxis with one or more fixed or anchored fiat boundaries.
Subdivision of cardinal body part, each instance of which is a regional part of some head proper.
Immaterial anatomical entity, each instance of which has three spatial dimensions.
Anatomical cluster in which parts of two or more anatomical structures establish physical continuity with one another or intermingle their component parts.
Facial hair grown on the outer surface of the upper lip. It may or may not be accompanied by a type of beard, a facial hair style grown and cropped to cover most of the lower half of the face.
Fleshy fold which surrounds the opening of the mouth.
Region of labial part of mouth sharing upper or lower boundary of oral orifice.
Vertical groove in the upper lip.
Organ component, each instance of which is an inneer layer or region of some organ.
Organ component, each instance of which is an outer layer or region of some organ.
Part of the pectoral area of the chest, each instance of which is an area of the pectoral chest.

label.value: region of pectoral part of chest

definition.value: Region of the pectoral part of the chest; each instance of which is an area of the anterior chest.
The depression or scar on the abdomen that marks the former site of attachment of the umbilical cord.
The pit in the center of the abdominal wall marking the point where the umbilical cord entered in the fetus.
Anatomical structure which is demarcated by bona fide or fiat boundaries within a cell.
Anatomical entity, each instance of which has three or fewer spatial dimensions.
Organ segment which is a regional part of the forebrain.

Organ component of neuraxis that has as its parts the cerebral cortex, cerebral white matter, basal ganglia, septum and fornix, as well as subcortical gray and white matter structures. There is only one telencephalon.
Any of various parts of the breast.
an anatomical entity is an object that is a structural part (material or immaterial) of a biological entity.
Portion of body fluid suspension which consists of spermatozoa and seminal plasma.
Portion of secreted substance produced prostatic glands, bulbourethral glands or the seminal vesicles.
Subdivision of frontal part of head bounded by anterior hairline and the eyebrows.
The part of the face above the eyes.
Anatomical structure, each instance of which has as its parts one or more ordered aggregates of some nucleotide, amino acid fatty acid or sugar molecules bonded to one another.
Developmental organism from 8 weeks of gestation to birth.

The unborn young of a viviparous mammal, in the postembryonic period, after the major structures have been outlined. In humans, the unborn young from the end of the eighth week after conception until birth, as distinguished from the earlier embryo, mammalian.
Excretion in semisolid state processed by the intestine.
Subdivision of larynx, each instance of which is a regional part of the larynx.

Anatomical cluster which has as its direct parts all or some members of two or more organ subclasses and one or more organ part subclasses which are grouped together according to some shared attributes.
An organ zone of the glans penis.
An organ zone of the ovary.
A boundary entity of the ovary, each instance of which has one spatial dimension.
Physical anatomical entity, each instance of which is a three-dimensional space, surface, line or point associated with some material anatomical entity.
Anatomical structure present after birth.
Anatomical entity that has mass.

Anatomical structure, which is a subdivision of a cardinal body part; it may exclude bones; is demarcated from other subdivisions of the same cardinal body part by anatomical surfaces or lines or topographical references; together with other contiguous subdivisions of the same cardinal body part, it constitutes a cardinal body part. anatomical structure, each instance of which is a regional part of some cardinal body part; it has as its constitutional part some subdivision of the integument, such that for each instance of cardinal body part the meronymic sum of its cardinal subdivisions constitutes the instance of cardinal body part.
